\lang1033 Not for the first time, an argument had broken out over breakfast at number four, Privet Drive. Mr. Vernon Durs\-ley had been woken in the early hours of the morning by a loud, hooting noise from his nephew Harry\rquote s room.\par
\lang3081\ldblquote Third time this week!\rdblquote  he roared across the table. \ldblquote If you can\rquote t control that owl, it\rquote ll have to go!\rdblquote\par
Harry tried, yet again, to explain.\par
\ldblquote She\rquote s \i bored,\i0\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote She\rquote s used to flying around outside. If I could just let her out at night \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do I look stupid?\rdblquote  snarled Uncle Vernon, a bit of fried egg dan\-gling from his bushy mustache. \ldblquote I know what\rquote ll happen if that owl\rquote s let out.\rdblquote\par
He exchanged dark looks with his wife, Petunia.\par
Harry tried to argue back but his words were drowned by a long, loud belch from the Dursleys\rquote  son, Dudley.\par
\ldblquote I want more bacon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s more in the frying pan, sweetums,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia, turning misty eyes on her massive son. \ldblquote We must build you up while we\rquote ve got the chance. \'85 I don\rquote t like the sound of that school food. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nonsense, Petunia, I never went hungry when \i I\i0  was at Smelt\-ings,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon heartily. \ldblquote Dudley gets enough, don\rquote t you, son?\rdblquote\par
Dudley, who was so large his bottom drooped over either side of the kitchen chair, grinned and turned to Harry.\par
\ldblquote Pass the frying pan.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve forgotten the magic word,\rdblquote  said Harry irritably.\par
The effect of this simple sentence on the rest of the family was incredible: Dudley gasped and fell off his chair with a crash that shook the whole kitchen; Mrs. Dursley gave a small scream and clapped her hands to her mouth; Mr. Dursley jumped to his feet, veins throbbing in his temples.\par
\ldblquote I meant \lquote please\rquote !\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote WHAT HAVE I TOLD YOU,\rdblquote  thundered his uncle, spraying spit over the table, \ldblquote ABOUT SAYING THE \lquote M\rquote  WORD IN OUR HOUSE?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But I \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote HOW DARE YOU THREATEN DUDLEY!\rdblquote  roared Uncle Vernon, pounding the table with his fist.\par
\ldblquote I just \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I WARNED YOU! I WILL NOT TOLERATE MENTION OF YOUR ABNORMALITY UNDER THIS ROOF!\rdblquote\par
Harry stared from his purple-faced uncle to his pale aunt, who was trying to heave Dudley to his feet.\par
\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote\i all right\i0  \'85\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon sat back down, breathing like a winded rhinoceros and watching Harry closely out of the corners of his small, sharp eyes.\par
Ever since Harry had come home for the summer holidays, Un\-cle Vernon had been treating him like a bomb that might go off at any moment, because Harry Potter \i wasn\rquote t\i0  a normal boy. As a mat\-ter of fact, he was as not normal as it is possible to be.\par
Harry Potter was a wizard \emdash  a wizard fresh from his first year at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. And if the Dursleys were unhappy to have him back for the holidays, it was nothing to how Harry felt.\par
He missed Hogwarts so much it was like having a constant stomachache. He missed the castle, with its secret passageways and ghosts, his classes (though perhaps not Snape, the Potions master), the mail arriving by owl, eating banquets in the Great Hall, sleep\-ing in his four-poster bed in the tower dormitory, visiting the gamekeeper, Hagrid, in his cabin next to the Forbidden Forest in the grounds, and, especially, Quidditch, the most popular sport in the wizarding world (six tall goal posts, four flying balls, and four\-teen players on broomsticks).\par
All Harry\rquote s spellbooks, his wand, robes, cauldron, and top-of-the-line Nimbus Two Thousand broomstick had been locked in a cupboard under the stairs by Uncle Vernon the instant Harry had come home. What did the Dursleys care if Harry lost his place on the House Quidditch team because he hadn\rquote t practiced all sum\-mer? What was it to the Dursleys if Harry went back to school without any of his homework done? The Dursleys were what wiz\-ards called Muggles (not a drop of magical blood in their veins), and as far as they were concerned, having a wizard in the family was a matter of deepest shame. Uncle Vernon had even padlocked Harry\rquote s owl, Hedwig, inside her cage, to stop her from carrying messages to anyone in the wizarding world.\par
Harry looked nothing like the rest of the family. Uncle Vernon was large and neckless, with an enormous black mustache; Aunt Petunia was horse-faced and bony; Dudley was blond, pink, and porky. Harry, on the other hand, was small and skinny, with bril\-liant green eyes and jet-black hair that was always untidy. He wore round glasses, and on his forehead was a thin, lightning-shaped scar.\par
It was this scar that made Harry so particularly unusual, even for a wizard. This scar was the only hint of Harry\rquote s very mysterious past, of the reason he had been left on the Dursleys\rquote  doorstep eleven years before.\par
At the age of one year old, Harry had somehow survived a curse from the greatest Dark sorcerer of all time, Lord Voldemort, whose name most witches and wizards still feared to speak. Harry\rquote s par\-ents had died in Voldemort\rquote s attack, but Harry had escaped with his lightning scar, and somehow \emdash  nobody understood why \emdash  Voldemort\rquote s powers had been destroyed the instant he had failed to kill Harry.\par
So Harry had been brought up by his dead mother\rquote s sister and her husband. He had spent ten years with the Dursleys, never un\-derstanding why he kept making odd things happen without meaning to, believing the Dursleys\rquote  story that he had got his scar in the car crash that had killed his parents.\par
And then, exactly a year ago, Hogwarts had written to Harry, and the whole story had come out. Harry had taken up his place at wizard school, where he and his scar were famous \'85 but now the school year was over, and he was back with the Dursleys for the summer, back to being treated like a dog that had rolled in some\-thing smelly.\par
The Dursleys hadn\rquote t even remembered that today happened to be Harry\rquote s twelfth birthday. Of course, his hopes hadn\rquote t been high; they\rquote d never given him a real present, let alone a cake \emdash  but to ig\-nore it completely \'85\par
At that moment, Uncle Vernon cleared his throat importantly and said, \ldblquote Now, as we all know, today is a very important day.\rdblquote\par
Harry looked up, hardly daring to believe it.\par
\ldblquote This could well be the day I make the biggest deal of my ca\-reer,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon.\par
Harry went back to his toast. \i Of course,\i0  he thought bitterly, \i Un\-cle Vernon was talking about the stupid dinner party.\i0  He\rquote d been talk\-ing of nothing else for two weeks. Some rich builder and his wife were coming to dinner and Uncle Vernon was hoping to get a huge order from him (Uncle Vernon\rquote s company made drills).\par
\ldblquote I think we should run through the schedule one more time,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote We should all be in position at eight o\rquote clock. Petunia, you will be \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In the lounge,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia promptly, \ldblquote waiting to wel\-come them graciously to our home.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good, good. And Dudley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be waiting to open the door.\rdblquote  Dudley put on a foul, sim\-pering smile. \ldblquote May I take your coats, Mr. and Mrs. Mason?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ll \i love\i0  him!\rdblquote  cried Aunt Petunia rapturously.\par
\ldblquote Excellent, Dudley,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon. Then he rounded on Harry. \ldblquote And \i you\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be in my bedroom, making no noise and pretending I\rquote m not there,\rdblquote  said Harry tonelessly.\par
\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon nastily. \ldblquote I will lead them into the lounge, introduce you, Petunia, and pour them drinks. At eight-fifteen \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll announce dinner,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia.\par
\ldblquote And, Dudley, you\rquote ll say \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote May I take you through to the dining room, Mrs. Mason?\rdblquote  said Dudley, offering his fat arm to an invisible woman.\par
\ldblquote My perfect little gentleman!\rdblquote  sniffed Aunt Petunia.\par
\ldblquote And \i you\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon viciously to Harry.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be in my room, making no noise and pretending I\rquote m not there,\rdblquote  said Harry dully.\par
\ldblquote Precisely. Now, we should aim to get in a few good compli\-ments at dinner. Petunia, any ideas?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Vernon tells me you\rquote re a \i wonderful\i0  golfer, Mr. Mason. \'85 \i Do \i0 tell me where you bought your dress, Mrs. Mason. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Perfect \'85 Dudley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How about \emdash  \lquote We had to write an essay about our hero at school, Mr. Mason, and \i I\i0  wrote about \i you.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\par
This was too much for both Aunt Petunia and Harry. Aunt Petu\-nia burst into tears and hugged her son, while Harry ducked under the table so they wouldn\rquote t see him laughing.\par
\ldblquote And you, boy?\rdblquote\par
Harry fought to keep his face straight as he emerged.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be in my room, making no noise and pretending I\rquote m not there,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote Too right, you will,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon forcefully. \ldblquote The Ma\-sons don\rquote t know anything about you and it\rquote s going to stay that way. When dinner\rquote s over, you take Mrs. Mason back to the lounge for coffee, Petunia, and I\rquote ll bring the subject around to drills. With any luck, I\rquote ll have the deal signed and sealed before the news at ten. We\rquote ll be shopping for a vacation home in Majorca this time to\-morrow.\rdblquote\par
Harry couldn\rquote t feel too excited about this. He didn\rquote t think the Dursleys would like him any better in Majorca than they did on Privet Drive.\par
\ldblquote Right \emdash  I\rquote m off into town to pick up the dinner jackets for Dudley and me. And \i you,\i0\rdblquote  he snarled at Harry. \ldblquote You stay out of your aunt\rquote s way while she\rquote s cleaning.\rdblquote\par
Harry left through the back door. It was a brilliant, sunny day. He crossed the lawn, slumped down on the garden bench, and sang under his breath:\par
\ldblquote Happy birthday to me \'85 happy birthday to me \'85\rdblquote\par
No cards, no presents, and he would be spending the evening pretending not to exist. He gazed miserably into the hedge. He had never felt so lonely. More than anything else at Hogwarts, more even than playing Quidditch, Harry missed his best friends, Ron Weasley and Hermione Granger. They, however, didn\rquote t seem to be missing him at all. Neither of them had written to him all summer, even though Ron had said he was going to ask Harry to come and stay.\par
Countless times, Harry had been on the point of unlocking Hedwig\rquote s cage by magic and sending her to Ron and Hermione with a letter, but it wasn\rquote t worth the risk. Underage wizards weren\rquote t allowed to use magic outside of school. Harry hadn\rquote t told the Dursleys this; he knew it was only their terror that he might turn them all into dung beetles that stopped them from locking \i him\i0  in the cupboard under the stairs with his wand and broomstick. For the first couple of weeks back, Harry had enjoyed muttering non\-sense words under his breath and watching Dudley tearing out of the room as fast as his fat legs would carry him. But the long silence from Ron and Hermione had made Harry feel so cut off from the magical world that even taunting Dudley had lost its appeal \emdash  and now Ron and Hermione had forgotten his birthday.\par
What wouldn\rquote t he give now for a message from Hogwarts? From any witch or wizard? He\rquote d almost be glad of a sight of his arch\-enemy, Draco Malfoy, just to be sure it hadn\rquote t all been a dream. \'85\par
Not that his whole year at Hogwarts had been fun. At the very end of last term, Harry had come face-to-face with none other than Lord Voldemort himself. Voldemort might be a ruin of his former self, but he was still terrifying, still cunning, still determined to re\-gain power. Harry had slipped through Voldemort\rquote s clutches for a second time, but it had been a narrow escape, and even now, weeks later, Harry kept waking in the night, drenched in cold sweat, won\-dering where Voldemort was now, remembering his livid face, his wide, mad eyes \emdash\par
Harry suddenly sat bolt upright on the garden bench. He had been staring absent-mindedly into the hedge \emdash  \i and the hedge was staring back.\i0  Two enormous green eyes had appeared among the leaves.\par
Harry jumped to his feet just as a jeering voice floated across the lawn.\par
\ldblquote I know what day it is,\rdblquote  sang Dudley, waddling toward him.\par
The huge eyes blinked and vanished.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry, not taking his eyes off the spot where they had been.\par
\ldblquote I know what day it is,\rdblquote  Dudley repeated, coming right up to him.\par
\ldblquote Well done,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote So you\rquote ve finally learned the days of the week.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Today\rquote s your \i birthday,\i0\rdblquote  sneered Dudley. \ldblquote How come you haven\rquote t got any cards? Haven\rquote t you even got friends at that freak place?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Better not let your mum hear you talking about my school,\rdblquote  said Harry coolly.\par
Dudley hitched up his trousers, which were slipping down his fat bottom.\par
\ldblquote Why\rquote re you staring at the hedge?\rdblquote  he said suspiciously.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m trying to decide what would be the best spell to set it on fire,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Dudley stumbled backward at once, a look of panic on his fat face.\par
\ldblquote You c-can\rquote t \emdash  Dad told you you\rquote re not to do m-magic \emdash  he said he\rquote ll chuck you out of the house \emdash  and you haven\rquote t got any\-where else to go \emdash  you haven\rquote t got any \i friends\i0  to take you \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Jiggery pokery\i0 !\rdblquote  said Harry in a fierce voice. \ldblquote\i Hocus pocus\i0  \emdash  \i squiggly wiggly\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote MUUUUUUM!\rdblquote  howled Dudley, tripping over his feet as he dashed back toward the house. \ldblquote MUUUUM! He\rquote s doing you know what!\rdblquote\par
Harry paid dearly for his moment of fun. As neither Dudley nor the hedge was in any way hurt, Aunt Petunia knew he hadn\rquote t really done magic, but he still had to duck as she aimed a heavy blow at his head with the soapy frying pan. Then she gave him work to do, with the promise he wouldn\rquote t eat again until he\rquote d finished.\par
While Dudley lolled around watching and eating ice cream, Harry cleaned the windows, washed the car, mowed the lawn, trimmed the flowerbeds, pruned and watered the roses, and re\-painted the garden bench. The sun blazed overhead, burning the back of his neck. Harry knew he shouldn\rquote t have risen to Dudley\rquote s bait, but Dudley had said the very thing Harry had been thinking himself \'85 maybe he \i didn\rquote t\i0  have any friends at Hogwarts. \'85\i\par
Wish they could see famous Harry Potter now,\i0  he thought savagely as he spread manure on the flower beds, his back aching, sweat run\-ning down his face.\par
It was half past seven in the evening when at last, exhausted, he heard Aunt Petunia calling him.\par
\ldblquote Get in here! And walk on the newspaper!\rdblquote\par
Harry moved gladly into the shade of the gleaming kitchen. On top of the fridge stood tonight\rquote s pudding: a huge mound of whipped cream and sugared violets. A loin of roast pork was siz\-zling in the oven.\par
\ldblquote Eat quickly! The Masons will be here soon!\rdblquote  snapped Aunt Petunia, pointing to two slices of bread and a lump of cheese on the kitchen table. She was already wearing a salmon-pink cocktail dress.\par
Harry washed his hands and bolted down his pitiful supper. The moment he had finished, Aunt Petunia whisked away his plate. \ldblquote Upstairs! Hurry!\rdblquote\par
As he passed the door to the living room, Harry caught a glimpse of Uncle Vernon and Dudley in bow ties and dinner jack\-ets. He had only just reached the upstairs landing when the door\-bell rang and Uncle Vernon\rquote s furious face appeared at the foot of the stairs.\par
\ldblquote Remember, boy \emdash  one sound \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry crossed to his bedroom on tiptoe, slipped inside, closed the door, and turned to collapse on his bed.\par
The trouble was, there was already someone sitting on it.\par
\lang1033\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\page\fs36 Chapter 2\par
\pard\qc Dobby\rquote s Warning\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang3081\fs24\par
\lang1033 Harry managed not to shout out, but it was a close thing. The little creature on the bed had large, bat-like ears and bulging green eyes the size of tennis balls. Harry knew instantly that this was what had been watching him out of the garden hedge that morning.\par
\lang3081 As they stared at each other, Harry heard Dudley\rquote s voice from the hall.\par
\ldblquote May I take your coats, Mr. and Mrs. Mason?\rdblquote\par
The creature slipped off the bed and bowed so low that the end of its long, thin nose touched the carpet. Harry noticed that it was wearing what looked like an old pillowcase, with rips for arm- and leg-holes.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  hello,\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter!\rdblquote  said the creature in a high-pitched voice Harry was sure would carry down the stairs. \ldblquote So long has Dobby wanted to meet you, sir \'85 Such an honor it is. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Th-thank you,\rdblquote  said Harry, edging along the wall and sinking into his desk chair, next to Hedwig, who was asleep in her large cage. He wanted to ask, \ldblquote What are you?\rdblquote  but thought it would sound too rude, so instead he said, \ldblquote Who are you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dobby, sir. Just Dobby. Dobby the house-elf,\rdblquote  said the crea\-ture.\par
\ldblquote Oh \emdash  really?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Er \emdash  I don\rquote t want to be rude or anything, but \emdash  this isn\rquote t a great time for me to have a house-elf in my bedroom.\rdblquote\par
Aunt Petunia\rquote s high, false laugh sounded from the living room. The elf hung his head.\par
\ldblquote Not that I\rquote m not pleased to meet you,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, \ldblquote but, er, is there any particular reason you\rquote re here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, yes, sir,\rdblquote  said Dobby earnestly. \ldblquote Dobby has come to tell you, sir \'85 it is difficult, sir \'85 Dobby wonders where to be\-gin. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sit down,\rdblquote  said Harry politely, pointing at the bed.\par
To his horror, the elf burst into tears \emdash  very noisy tears.\par
\ldblquote\i S-sit down\i0 !\rdblquote  he wailed. \ldblquote\i Never\i0  \i\'85 never ever\i0  \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry thought he heard the voices downstairs falter.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry,\rdblquote  he whispered, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean to offend you or any\-thing \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Offend Dobby!\rdblquote  choked the elf. \ldblquote Dobby has \i never\i0  been asked to sit down by a wizard \emdash  like an \i equal\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry, trying to say \ldblquote Shh!\rdblquote  and look comforting at the same time, ushered Dobby back onto the bed where he sat hiccoughing, looking like a large and very ugly doll. At last he managed to con\-trol himself, and sat with his great eyes fixed on Harry in an ex\-pression of watery adoration.\par
\ldblquote You can\rquote t have met many decent wizards,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to cheer him up.\par
Dobby shook his head. Then, without warning, he leapt up and started banging his head furiously on the window, shouting, \ldblquote\i Bad \i0 Dobby! \i Bad\i0  Dobby!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t \emdash  what are you doing?\rdblquote  Harry hissed, springing up and pulling Dobby back onto the bed \emdash  Hedwig had woken up with a particularly loud screech and was beating her wings wildly against the bars of her cage.\par
\ldblquote Dobby had to punish himself, sir,\rdblquote  said the elf, who had gone slightly cross-eyed. \ldblquote Dobby almost spoke ill of his family, sir. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Your family?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The wizard family Dobby serves, sir. \'85 Dobby is a house-elf \emdash  bound to serve one house and one family forever. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do they know you\rquote re here?\rdblquote  asked Harry curiously.\par
Dobby shuddered.\par
\ldblquote Oh, no, sir, no \'85 Dobby will have to punish himself most grievously for coming to see you, sir. Dobby will have to shut his ears in the oven door for this. If they ever knew, sir \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But won\rquote t they notice if you shut your ears in the oven door?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dobby doubts it, sir. Dobby is always having to punish himself for something, sir. They lets Dobby get on with it, sir. Sometimes they reminds me to do extra punishments. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But why don\rquote t you leave? Escape?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A house-elf must be set free, sir. And the family will never set Dobby free \'85 Dobby will serve the family until he dies, sir. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry stared.\par
\ldblquote And I thought I had it bad staying here for another four weeks,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote This makes the Dursleys sound almost human. Can\rquote t any\-one help you? Can\rquote t I?\rdblquote\par
Almost at once, Harry wished he hadn\rquote t spoken. Dobby dis\-solved again into wails of gratitude.\par
\ldblquote Please,\rdblquote  Harry whispered frantically, \ldblquote please be quiet. If the Dursleys hear anything, if they know you\rquote re here \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter asks if he can help Dobby \'85 Dobby has heard of your greatness, sir, but of your goodness, Dobby never knew. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry, who was feeling distinctly hot in the face, said, \ldblquote What\-ever you\rquote ve heard about my greatness is a load of rubbish. I\rquote m not even top of my year at Hogwarts; that\rquote s Hermione, she \emdash\rdblquote\par
But he stopped quickly, because thinking about Hermione was painful.\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter is humble and modest,\rdblquote  said Dobby reverently, his orb-like eyes aglow. \ldblquote Harry Potter speaks not of his triumph over He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Voldemort?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Dobby clapped his hands over his bat ears and moaned, \ldblquote Ah, speak not the name, sir! Speak not the name!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote I know lots of people don\rquote t like it. My friend Ron \emdash\rdblquote\par
He stopped again. Thinking about Ron was painful, too.\par
Dobby leaned toward Harry, his eyes wide as headlights.\par
\ldblquote Dobby heard tell,\rdblquote  he said hoarsely, \ldblquote that Harry Potter met the Dark Lord for a second time, just weeks ago \'85 that Harry Potter escaped \i yet again.\i0\rdblquote\par
Harry nodded and Dobby\rquote s eyes suddenly shone with tears.\par
\ldblquote Ah, sir,\rdblquote  he gasped, dabbing his face with a corner of the grubby pillowcase he was wearing. \ldblquote Harry Potter is valiant and bold! He has braved so many dangers already! But Dobby has come to pro\-tect Harry Potter, to warn him, even if he \i does\i0  have to shut his ears in the oven door later. \'85 \i Harry Potter must not go back to Hogwarts.\i0\rdblquote\par
There was a silence broken only by the chink of knives and forks from downstairs and the distant rumble of Uncle Vernon\rquote s voice.\par
\ldblquote W-what?\rdblquote  Harry stammered. \ldblquote But I\rquote ve got to go back \emdash  term starts on September first. It\rquote s all that\rquote s keeping me going. You don\rquote t know what it\rquote s like here. I don\rquote t \i belong\i0  here. I belong in your world \emdash  at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no, no,\rdblquote  squeaked Dobby, shaking his head so hard his ears flapped. \ldblquote Harry Potter must stay where he is safe. He is too great, too good, to lose. If Harry Potter goes back to Hogwarts, he will be in mortal danger.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Harry in surprise.\par
