The assistant looked as though he wanted to stop them from leaving, but he barely came up to Hagrid\rquote s waist and seemed to think better of it. They hurried up the street, the Grangers shaking with fright and Mrs. Weasley beside herself with fury.\par
\ldblquote A \i fine\i0  example to set for your children \'85 \i brawling\i0  in pub\-lic \'85 \i what\i0  Gilderoy Lockhart must\rquote ve thought \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was pleased,\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t you hear him as we were leaving? He was asking that bloke from the \i Daily Prophet\i0  if he\rquote d be able to work the fight into his report \emdash  said it was all publicity \emdash\rdblquote\par
But it was a subdued group that headed back to the fireside in the Leaky Cauldron, where Harry, the Weasleys, and all their shop\-ping would be traveling back to the Burrow using Floo powder. They said good-bye to the Grangers, who were leaving the pub for the Muggle street on the other side; Mr. Weasley started to ask them how bus stops worked, but stopped quickly at the look on Mrs. Weasley\rquote s face.\par
