\lang1033 The end of the summer vacation came too quickly for Harry\rquote s liking. He was looking forward to getting back to Hogwarts, but his month at the Burrow had been the happiest of his life. It was difficult not to feel jealous of Ron when he thought of the Dursleys and the sort of welcome he could expect next time he turned up on Privet Drive.\par
\lang3081 On their last evening, Mrs. Weasley conjured up a sumptuous dinner that included all of Harry\rquote s favorite things, ending with a mouthwatering treacle pudding. Fred and George rounded off the evening with a display of Filibuster fireworks; they filled the kitchen with red and blue stars that bounced from ceiling to wall for at least half an hour. Then it was time for a last mug of hot chocolate and bed.\par
It took a long while to get started next morning. They were up at dawn, but somehow they still seemed to have a great deal to do. Mrs. Weasley dashed about in a bad mood looking for spare socks and quills; people kept colliding on the stairs, half-dressed with bits of toast in their hands; and Mr. Weasley nearly broke his neck, trip\-ping over a stray chicken as he crossed the yard carrying Ginny\rquote s trunk to the car.\par
Harry couldn\rquote t see how eight people, six large trunks, two owls, and a rat were going to fit into one small Ford Anglia. He had reck\-oned, of course, without the special features that Mr. Weasley had added.\par
\ldblquote Not a word to Molly,\rdblquote  he whispered to Harry as he opened the trunk and showed him how it had been magically expanded so that the luggage fitted easily.\par
When at last they were all in the car, Mrs. Weasley glanced into the back seat, where Harry, Ron, Fred, George, and Percy were all sitting comfortably side by side, and said, \ldblquote Muggles \i do\i0  know more than we give them credit for, don\rquote t they?\rdblquote  She and Ginny got into the front seat, which had been stretched so that it resembled a park bench. \ldblquote I mean, you\rquote d never know it was this roomy from the out\-side, would you?\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley started up the engine and they trundled out of the yard, Harry turning back for a last look at the house. He barely had time to wonder when he\rquote d see it again when they were back \emdash  George had forgotten his box of Filibuster fireworks. Five minutes after that, they skidded to a halt in the yard so that Fred could run in for his broomstick. They had almost reached the highway when Ginny shrieked that she\rquote d left her diary. By the time she had clam\-bered back into the car, they were running very late, and tempers were running high.\par
Mr. Weasley glanced at his watch and then at his wife.\par
\ldblquote Molly, dear \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i No,\i0  Arthur \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No one would see \emdash  this little button here is an Invisibility Booster I installed \emdash  that\rquote d get us up in the air \emdash  then we fly above the clouds. We\rquote d be there in ten minutes and no one would be any the wiser \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I said \i no,\i0  Arthur, not in broad daylight \emdash\rdblquote\par
They reached King\rquote s Cross at a quarter to eleven. Mr. Weasley dashed across the road to get trolleys for their trunks and they all hurried into the station.\par
Harry had caught the Hogwarts Express the previous year. The tricky part was getting onto platform nine and three-quarters, which wasn\rquote t visible to the Muggle eye. What you had to do was walk through the solid barrier dividing platforms nine and ten. It didn\rquote t hurt, but it had to be done carefully so that none of the Muggles noticed you vanishing.\par
\ldblquote Percy first,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, looking nervously at the clock overhead, which showed they had only five minutes to disappear casually through the barrier.\par
Percy strode briskly forward and vanished. Mr. Weasley went next; Fred and George followed.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll take Ginny and you two come right after us,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley told Harry and Ron, grabbing Ginny\rquote s hand and setting off. In the blink of an eye they were gone.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s go together, we\rquote ve only got a minute,\rdblquote  Ron said to Harry.\par
Harry made sure that Hedwig\rquote s cage was safely wedged on top of his trunk and wheeled his trolley around to face the barrier. He felt perfectly confident; this wasn\rquote t nearly as uncomfortable as using Floo powder. Both of them bent low over the handles of their trol\-leys and walked purposefully toward the barrier, gathering speed. A few feet away from it, they broke into a run and \emdash\par
CRASH.\par
Both trolleys hit the barrier and bounced backward; Ron\rquote s trunk fell off with a loud thump, Harry was knocked off his feet, and Hedwig\rquote s cage bounced onto the shiny floor, and she rolled away, shrieking indignantly; people all around them stared and a guard nearby yelled, \ldblquote What in blazes d\rquote you think you\rquote re doing?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Lost control of the trolley,\rdblquote  Harry gasped, clutching his ribs as he got up. Ron ran to pick up Hedwig, who was causing such a scene that there was a lot of muttering about cruelty to animals from the surrounding crowd.\par
\ldblquote Why can\rquote t we get through?\rdblquote  Harry hissed to Ron.\par
\ldblquote I dunno \emdash\rdblquote\par
Ron looked wildly around. A dozen curious people were still watching them.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re going to miss the train,\rdblquote  Ron whispered. \ldblquote I don\rquote t under\-stand why the gateway\rquote s sealed itself \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry looked up at the giant clock with a sickening feeling in the pit of his stomach. Ten seconds \'85 nine seconds \'85\par
He wheeled his trolley forward cautiously until it was right against the barrier and pushed with all his might. The metal re\-mained solid.\par
Three seconds \'85 two seconds \'85 one second \'85\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s gone,\rdblquote  said Ron, sounding stunned. \ldblquote The train\rquote s left. What if Mum and Dad can\rquote t get back through to us? Have you got any Muggle money?\rdblquote\par
Harry gave a hollow laugh. \ldblquote The Dursleys haven\rquote t given me pocket money for about six years.\rdblquote\par
Ron pressed his ear to the cold barrier.\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t hear a thing,\rdblquote  he said tensely. \ldblquote What\rquote re we going to do? I don\rquote t know how long it\rquote ll take Mum and Dad to get back to us.\rdblquote\par
They looked around. People were still watching them, mainly because of Hedwig\rquote s continuing screeches.\par
\ldblquote I think we\rquote d better go and wait by the car,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote We\rquote re attracting too much atten \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  said Ron, his eyes gleaming. \ldblquote The car!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We can fly the car to Hogwarts!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But I thought \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re stuck, right? And we\rquote ve got to get to school, haven\rquote t we? And even underage wizards are allowed to use magic if it\rquote s a real emergency, section nineteen or something of the Restriction of Thingy \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But your mum and dad \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, pushing against the barrier again in the vain hope that it would give way. \ldblquote How will they get home?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They don\rquote t need the car!\rdblquote  said Ron impatiently. \ldblquote They know how to Apparate! You know, just vanish and reappear at home! They only bother with Floo powder and the car because we\rquote re all underage and we\rquote re not allowed to Apparate yet. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s feeling of panic turned suddenly to excitement.\par
\ldblquote Can you fly it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No problem,\rdblquote  said Ron, wheeling his trolley around to face the exit. \ldblquote C\rquote mon, let\rquote s go. If we hurry we\rquote ll be able to follow the Hog\-warts Express \emdash\rdblquote\par
And they marched off through the crowd of curious Muggles, out of the station and back onto the side road where the old Ford Anglia was parked.\par
Ron unlocked the cavernous trunk with a series of taps from his wand. They heaved their luggage back in, put Hedwig on the back seat, and got into the front.\par
\ldblquote Check that no one\rquote s watching,\rdblquote  said Ron, starting the ignition with another tap of his wand. Harry stuck his head out of the win\-dow: Traffic was rumbling along the main road ahead, but their street was empty.\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  he said.\par
Ron pressed a tiny silver button on the dashboard. The car around them vanished \emdash  and so did they. Harry could feel the seat vibrating beneath him, hear the engine, feel his hands on his knees and his glasses on his nose, but for all he could see, he had become a pair of eyeballs, floating a few feet above the ground in a dingy street full of parked cars.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s go,\rdblquote  said Ron\rquote s voice from his right.\par
And the ground and the dirty buildings on either side fell away, dropping out of sight as the car rose; in seconds, the whole of Lon\-don lay, smoky and glittering, below them.\par
Then there was a popping noise and the car, Harry, and Ron reappeared.\par
\ldblquote Uh-oh,\rdblquote  said Ron, jabbing at the Invisibility Booster. \ldblquote It\rquote s faulty \emdash\rdblquote\par
Both of them pummeled it. The car vanished. Then it flickered back again.\par
\ldblquote Hold on!\rdblquote  Ron yelled, and he slammed his foot on the accelerator; they shot straight into the low, woolly clouds and everything turned dull and foggy.\par
\ldblquote Now what?\rdblquote  said Harry, blinking at the solid mass of cloud pressing in on them from all sides.\par
\ldblquote We need to see the train to know what direction to go in,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Dip back down again \emdash  quickly \emdash\rdblquote\par
They dropped back beneath the clouds and twisted around in their seats, squinting at the ground.\par
\ldblquote I can see it!\rdblquote  Harry yelled. \ldblquote Right ahead \emdash  there!\rdblquote\par
The Hogwarts Express was streaking along below them like a scarlet snake.\par
\ldblquote Due north,\rdblquote  said Ron, checking the compass on the dashboard. \ldblquote Okay, we\rquote ll just have to check on it every half hour or so \emdash  hold on \emdash\rdblquote\par
And they shot up through the clouds. A minute later, they burst out into a blaze of sunlight.\par
It was a different world. The wheels of the car skimmed the sea of fluffy cloud, the sky a bright, endless blue under the blinding white sun.\par
\ldblquote All we\rquote ve got to worry about now are airplanes,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
They looked at each other and started to laugh; for a long time, they couldn\rquote t stop.\par
It was as though they had been plunged into a fabulous dream. This, thought Harry, was surely the only way to travel \emdash  past swirls and turrets of snowy cloud, in a car full of hot, bright sun\-light, with a fat pack of toffees in the glove compartment, and the prospect of seeing Fred\rquote s and George\rquote s jealous faces when they landed smoothly and spectacularly on the sweeping lawn in front of Hogwarts castle.\par
They made regular checks on the train as they flew farther and farther north, each dip beneath the clouds showing them a dif\-ferent view. London was soon far behind them, replaced by neat green fields that gave way in turn to wide, purplish moors, a great city alive with cars like multicolored ants, villages with tiny toy churches.\par
Several uneventful hours later, however, Harry had to admit that some of the fun was wearing off. The toffees had made them ex\-tremely thirsty and they had nothing to drink. He and Ron had pulled off their sweaters, but Harry\rquote s T-shirt was sticking to the back of his seat and his glasses kept sliding down to the end of his sweaty nose. He had stopped noticing the fantastic cloud shapes now and was thinking longingly of the train miles below, where you could buy ice-cold pumpkin juice from a trolley pushed by a plump witch. \i Why\i0  hadn\rquote t they been able to get onto platform nine and three-quarters?\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t be much further, can it?\rdblquote  croaked Ron, hours later still, as the sun started to sink into their floor of cloud, staining it a deep pink. \ldblquote Ready for another check on the train?\rdblquote\par
It was still right below them, winding its way past a snowcapped mountain. It was much darker beneath the canopy of clouds.\par
Ron put his foot on the accelerator and drove them upward again, but as he did so, the engine began to whine.\par
Harry and Ron exchanged nervous glances.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s probably just tired,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote It\rquote s never been this far be\-fore. \'85\rdblquote\par
And they both pretended not to notice the whining growing louder and louder as the sky became steadily darker. Stars were blossoming in the blackness. Harry pulled his sweater back on, try\-ing to ignore the way the windshield wipers were now waving fee\-bly, as though in protest.\par
\ldblquote Not far,\rdblquote  said Ron, more to the car than to Harry, \ldblquote not far now,\rdblquote  and he patted the dashboard nervously.\par
When they flew back beneath the clouds a little while later, they had to squint through the darkness for a landmark they knew.\par
\ldblquote\i There\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry shouted, making Ron and Hedwig jump. \ldblquote Straight ahead!\rdblquote\par
Silhouetted on the dark horizon, high on the cliff over the lake, stood the many turrets and towers of Hogwarts castle.\par
But the car had begun to shudder and was losing speed.\par
\ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  Ron said cajolingly, giving the steering wheel a lit\-tle shake, \ldblquote nearly there, come on \emdash\rdblquote\par
The engine groaned. Narrow jets of steam were issuing from un\-der the hood. Harry found himself gripping the edges of his seat very hard as they flew toward the lake.\par
The car gave a nasty wobble. Glancing out of his window, Harry saw the smooth, black, glassy surface of the water, a mile below. Ron\rquote s knuckles were white on the steering wheel. The car wobbled again.\par
\ldblquote Come \i on,\i0\rdblquote  Ron muttered.\par
They were over the lake \emdash  the castle was right ahead \emdash  Ron put his foot down.\par
There was a loud clunk, a splutter, and the engine died com\-pletely.\par
\ldblquote Uh-oh,\rdblquote  said Ron, into the silence.\par
The nose of the car dropped. They were falling, gathering speed, heading straight for the solid castle wall.\par
\ldblquote\i Noooooo\i0 !\rdblquote  Ron yelled, swinging the steering wheel around; they missed the dark stone wall by inches as the car turned in a great arc, soaring over the dark greenhouses, then the vegetable patch, and then out over the black lawns, losing altitude all the time.\par
Ron let go of the steering wheel completely and pulled his wand out of his back pocket \emdash\par
\ldblquote STOP! STOP!\rdblquote  he yelled, whacking the dashboard and the windshield, but they were still plummeting, the ground flying up toward them \emdash\par
\ldblquote WATCH OUT FOR THAT TREE!\rdblquote  Harry bellowed, lunging for the steering wheel, but too late \emdash\par
CRUNCH.\par
With an earsplitting bang of metal on wood, they hit the thick tree trunk and dropped to the ground with a heavy jolt. Steam was billowing from under the crumpled hood; Hedwig was shrieking in terror; a golf-ball-sized lump was throbbing on Harry\rquote s head where he had hit the windshield; and to his right, Ron let out a low, de\-spairing groan.\par
\ldblquote Are you okay?\rdblquote  Harry said urgently.\par
\ldblquote My wand,\rdblquote  said Ron, in a shaky voice. \ldblquote Look at my wand \emdash\rdblquote\par
It had snapped, almost in two; the tip was dangling limply, held on by a few splinters.\par
Harry opened his mouth to say he was sure they\rquote d be able to mend it up at the school, but he never even got started. At that very moment, something hit his side of the car with the force of a charging bull, sending him lurching sideways into Ron, just as an equally heavy blow hit the roof.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s happen \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
Ron gasped, staring through the windshield, and Harry looked around just in time to see a branch as thick as a python smash into it. The tree they had hit was attacking them. Its trunk was bent al\-most double, and its gnarled boughs were pummeling every inch of the car it could reach.\par
\ldblquote Aaargh!\rdblquote  said Ron as another twisted limb punched a large dent into his door; the windshield was now trembling under a hail of blows from knuckle-like twigs and a branch as thick as a battering ram was pounding furiously on the roof, which seemed to be cav\-ing \emdash\par
\ldblquote Run for it!\rdblquote  Ron shouted, throwing his full weight against his door, but next second he had been knocked backward into Harry\rquote s lap by a vicious uppercut from another branch.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re done for!\rdblquote  he moaned as the ceiling sagged, but suddenly the floor of the car was vibrating \emdash  the engine had restarted.\par
\ldblquote\i Reverse\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry yelled, and the car shot backward; the tree was still trying to hit them; they could hear its roots creaking as it al\-most ripped itself up, lashing out at them as they sped out of reach.\par
\ldblquote That,\rdblquote  panted Ron, \ldblquote was close. Well done, car \emdash\rdblquote\par
The car, however, had reached the end of its tether. With two sharp clunks, the doors flew open and Harry felt his seat tip side\-ways: Next thing he knew he was sprawled on the damp ground. Loud thuds told him that the car was ejecting their luggage from the trunk; Hedwig\rquote s cage flew through the air and burst open; she rose out of it with an angry screech and sped off toward the castle without a backward look. Then, dented, scratched, and steaming, the car rumbled off into the darkness, its rear lights blazing angrily.\par
\ldblquote Come back!\rdblquote  Ron yelled after it, brandishing his broken wand. \ldblquote Dad\rquote ll kill me!\rdblquote\par
But the car disappeared from view with one last snort from its exhaust.\par
\ldblquote Can you \i believe\i0  our luck?\rdblquote  said Ron miserably, bending down to pick up Scabbers. \ldblquote Of all the trees we could\rquote ve hit, we had to get one that hits back.\rdblquote\par
He glanced over his shoulder at the ancient tree, which was still flailing its branches threateningly.\par
\ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  said Harry wearily, \ldblquote we\rquote d better get up to the school. \'85\rdblquote\par
It wasn\rquote t at all the triumphant arrival they had pictured. Stiff, cold, and bruised, they seized the ends of their trunks and began dragging them up the grassy slope, toward the great oak front doors.\par
\ldblquote I think the feast\rquote s already started,\rdblquote  said Ron, dropping his trunk at the foot of the front steps and crossing quietly to look through a brightly lit window. \ldblquote Hey \emdash  Harry \emdash  come and look \emdash  it\rquote s the Sorting!\rdblquote\par
Harry hurried over and, together, he and Ron peered in at the Great Hall.\par
Innumerable candles were hovering in midair over four long, crowded tables, making the golden plates and goblets sparkle. Overhead, the bewitched ceiling, which always mirrored the sky outside, sparkled with stars.\par
Through the forest of pointed black Hogwarts hats, Harry saw a long line of scared-looking first years filing into the Hall. Ginny was among them, easily visible because of her vivid Weasley hair. Meanwhile, Professor McGonagall, a bespectacled witch with her hair in a tight bun, was placing the famous Hogwarts Sorting Hat on a stool before the newcomers.\par
Every year, this aged old hat, patched, frayed, and dirty, sorted new students into the four Hogwarts houses (Gryffindor, Huf\-flepuff, Ravenclaw, and Slytherin). Harry well remembered putting it on, exactly one year ago, and waiting, petrified, for its decision as it muttered aloud in his ear. For a few horrible seconds he had feared that the hat was going to put him in Slytherin, the House that had turned out more Dark witches and wizards than any other \emdash  but he had ended up in Gryffindor, along with Ron, Hermione, and the rest of the Weasleys. Last term, Harry and Ron had helped Gryffindor win the House Championship, beating Slytherin for the first time in seven years.\par
A very small, mousy-haired boy had been called forward to place the hat on his head. Harry\rquote s eyes wandered past him to where Pro\-fessor Dumbledore, the headmaster, sat watching the Sorting from the staff table, his long silver beard and half-moon glasses shining brightly in the candlelight. Several seats along, Harry saw Gilderoy Lockhart, dressed in robes of aquamarine. And there at the end was Hagrid, huge and hairy, drinking deeply from his goblet.\par
\ldblquote Hang on \'85\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Ron. \ldblquote There\rquote s an empty chair at the staff table. \'85 Where\rquote s Snape?\rdblquote\par
Professor Severus Snape was Harry\rquote s least favorite teacher. Harry also happened to be Snape\rquote s least favorite student. Cruel, sarcastic, and disliked by everybody except the students from his own House (Slytherin), Snape taught Potions.\par
\ldblquote Maybe he\rquote s ill!\rdblquote  said Ron hopefully.\par
\ldblquote Maybe he\rquote s \i left,\i0\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote because he missed out on the De\-fense Against the Dark Arts job \i again\i0 !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Or he might have been \i sacked\i0 !\rdblquote  said Ron enthusiastically. \ldblquote I mean, everyone hates him \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Or maybe,\rdblquote  said a very cold voice right behind them, \ldblquote he\rquote s waiting to hear why you two didn\rquote t arrive on the school train.\rdblquote\par
Harry spun around. There, his black robes rippling in a cold breeze, stood Severus Snape. He was a thin man with sallow skin, a hooked nose, and greasy, shoulder-length black hair, and at this moment, he was smiling in a way that told Harry he and Ron were in very deep trouble.\par
\ldblquote Follow me,\rdblquote  said Snape.\par
Not daring even to look at each other, Harry and Ron followed Snape up the steps into the vast, echoing entrance hall, which was lit with flaming torches. A delicious smell of food was wafting from the Great Hall, but Snape led them away from the warmth and light, down a narrow stone staircase that led into the dungeons.\par
\ldblquote In!\rdblquote  he said, opening a door halfway down the cold passageway and pointing.\par
They entered Snape\rquote s office, shivering. The shadowy walls were lined with shelves of large glass jars, in which floated all manner of revolting things Harry didn\rquote t really want to know the name of at the moment. The fireplace was dark and empty. Snape closed the door and turned to look at them.\par
\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  he said softly, \ldblquote the train isn\rquote t good enough for the famous Harry Potter and his faithful sidekick, Weasley. Wanted to arrive with a \i bang,\i0  did we, boys?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, sir, it was the barrier at King\rquote s Cross, it \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Silence!\rdblquote  said Snape coldly. \ldblquote What have you done with the car?\rdblquote\par
Ron gulped. This wasn\rquote t the first time Snape had given Harry the impression of being able to read minds. But a moment later, he un\-derstood, as Snape unrolled today\rquote s issue of the \i Evening Prophet.\i0\par
\ldblquote You were seen,\rdblquote  he hissed, showing them the headline: \i FLY\-ING FORD ANGLIA MYSTIFIES MUGGLES. \i0 He began to read aloud: \ldblquote Two Muggles in London, convinced they saw an old car flying over the Post Office tower \'85 at noon in Norfolk, Mrs. Hetty Bayliss, while hanging out her washing \'85 Mr. Angus Fleet, of Peebles, reported to police \'85 Six or seven Muggles in all. I be\-lieve \i your \i0 father works in the Misuse of Muggle Artifacts Office?\rdblquote  he said, looking up at Ron and smiling still more nastily. \ldblquote Dear, dear \'85 his own son \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry felt as though he\rquote d just been walloped in the stomach by one of the mad tree\rquote s larger branches. If anyone found out Mr. Weasley had bewitched the car \'85 he hadn\rquote t thought of that. \'85\par
\ldblquote I noticed, in my search of the park, that considerable damage seems to have been done to a very valuable Whomping Willow,\rdblquote  Snape went on.\par
\ldblquote That tree did more damage to \i us\i0  than we \emdash\rdblquote  Ron blurted out.\par
\ldblquote\i Silence\i0 !\rdblquote  snapped Snape again. \ldblquote Most unfortunately, you are not in my House and the decision to expel you does not rest with me. I shall go and fetch the people who \i do\i0  have that happy power. You will wait here.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Ron stared at each other, white-faced. Harry didn\rquote t feel hungry anymore. He now felt extremely sick. He tried not to look at a large, slimy something suspended in green liquid on a shelf behind Snape\rquote s desk. If Snape had gone to fetch Professor McGonagall, head of Gryffindor House, they were hardly any bet\-ter off. She might be fairer than Snape, but she was still extremely strict.\par
Ten minutes later, Snape returned, and sure enough it was Pro\-fessor McGonagall who accompanied him. Harry had seen Profes\-sor McGonagall angry on several occasions, but either he had forgotten just how thin her mouth could go, or he had never seen her this angry before. She raised her wand the moment she entered; Harry and Ron both flinched, but she merely pointed it at the empty fireplace, where flames suddenly erupted.\par
\ldblquote Sit,\rdblquote  she said, and they both backed into chairs by the fire.\par
\ldblquote Explain,\rdblquote  she said, her glasses glinting ominously.\par
Ron launched into the story, starting with the barrier at the sta\-tion refusing to let them through.\par
\ldblquote\emdash  so we had no choice, Professor, we couldn\rquote t get on the train.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why didn\rquote t you send us a letter by owl? I believe \i you\i0  have an owl?\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall said coldly to Harry.\par
Harry gaped at her. Now she\rquote d said it, that seemed the obvious thing to have done.\par
\ldblquote I \emdash  I didn\rquote t think \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, \ldblquote is obvious.\rdblquote\par
There was a knock on the office door and Snape, now looking happier than ever, opened it. There stood the headmaster, Professor Dumbledore.\par
