\lang1033 Harry spent a lot of time over the next few days dodging out of sight whenever he saw Gilderoy Lockhart coming down a corridor. Harder to avoid was Colin Creevey, who seemed to have memorized Harry\rquote s schedule. Nothing seemed to give Colin a bigger thrill than to say, \ldblquote All right, Harry?\rdblquote  six or seven times a day and hear, \ldblquote Hello, Colin,\rdblquote  back, however exasperated Harry sounded when he said it.\par
\lang3081 Hedwig was still angry with Harry about the disasterous car journey and Ron\rquote s wand was still malfunctioning, surpassing itself on Friday morning by shooting out of Ron\rquote s hand in Charms and hitting tiny old Professor Flitwick squarely between the eyes, creat\-ing a large, throbbing green boil where it had struck. So with one thing and another, Harry was quite glad to reach the weekend. He, Ron, and Hermione were planning to visit Hagrid on Saturday morning. Harry, however, was shaken awake several hours earlier than he would have liked by Oliver Wood, Captain of the Gryf\-findor Quidditch team.\par
\ldblquote Whassamatter?\rdblquote  said Harry groggily.\par
\ldblquote Quidditch practice!\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Come on!\rdblquote\par
Harry squinted at the window. There was a thin mist hanging across the pink-and-gold sky. Now that he was awake, he couldn\rquote t understand how he could have slept through the racket the birds were making.\par
\ldblquote Oliver,\rdblquote  Harry croaked. \ldblquote It\rquote s the crack of dawn.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Wood. He was a tall and burly sixth year and, at the moment, his eyes were gleaming with a crazed enthusiasm. \ldblquote It\rquote s part of our new training program. Come on, grab your broom, and let\rquote s go,\rdblquote  said Wood heartily. \ldblquote None of the other teams have started training yet; we\rquote re going to be first off the mark this year \emdash\rdblquote\par
Yawning and shivering slightly, Harry climbed out of bed and tried to find his Quidditch robes.\par
\ldblquote Good man,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Meet you on the field in fifteen min\-utes.\rdblquote\par
When he\rquote d found his scarlet team robes and pulled on his cloak for warmth, Harry scribbled a note to Ron explaining where he\rquote d gone and went down the spiral staircase to the common room, his Nimbus Two Thousand on his shoulder. He had just reached the portrait hole when there was a clatter behind him and Colin Creevey came dashing down the spiral staircase, his camera swinging madly around his neck and something clutched in his hand.\par
\ldblquote I heard someone saying your name on the stairs, Harry! Look what I\rquote ve got here! I\rquote ve had it developed, I wanted to show you \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry looked bemusedly at the photograph Colin was brandish\-ing under his nose.\par
A moving, black-and-white Lockhart was tugging hard on an arm Harry recognized as his own. He was pleased to see that his photographic self was putting up a good fight and refusing to be dragged into view. As Harry watched, Lockhart gave up and slumped, panting, against the white edge of the picture.\par
\ldblquote Will you sign it?\rdblquote  said Colin eagerly.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry flatly, glancing around to check that the room was really deserted. \ldblquote Sorry, Colin, I\rquote m in a hurry \emdash  Quidditch practice \emdash\rdblquote\par
He climbed through the portrait hole.\par
\ldblquote Oh, wow! Wait for me! I\rquote ve never watched a Quidditch game before!\rdblquote\par
Colin scrambled through the hole after him.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote ll be really boring,\rdblquote  Harry said quickly, but Colin ignored him, his face shining with excitement.\par
\ldblquote You were the youngest House player in a hundred years, weren\rquote t you, Harry? Weren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Colin, trotting alongside him. \ldblquote You must be brilliant. I\rquote ve never flown. Is it easy? Is that your own broom? Is that the best one there is?\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t know how to get rid of him. It was like having an extremely talkative shadow.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t really understand Quidditch,\rdblquote  said Colin breathlessly. \ldblquote Is it true there are four balls? And two of them fly around trying to knock people off their brooms?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry heavily, resigned to explaining the complicated rules of Quidditch. \ldblquote They\rquote re called Bludgers. There are two Beaters on each team who carry clubs to beat the Bludgers away from their side. Fred and George Weasley are the Gryffindor Beaters.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what are the other balls for?\rdblquote  Colin asked, tripping down a couple of steps because he was gazing open-mouthed at Harry.\par
\ldblquote Well, the Quaffle \emdash  that\rquote s the biggish red one \emdash  is the one that scores goals. Three Chasers on each team throw the Quaffle to each other and try and get it through the goal posts at the end of the pitch \emdash  they\rquote re three long poles with hoops on the end.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And the fourth ball \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  is the Golden Snitch,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote and it\rquote s very small, very fast, and difficult to catch. But that\rquote s what the Seeker\rquote s got to do, because a game of Quidditch doesn\rquote t end until the Snitch has been caught. And whichever team\rquote s Seeker gets the Snitch earns his team an extra hundred and fifty points.\rdblquote\par
