He scrawled an enormous loopy signature on the note and handed it back to Hermione.\par
\ldblquote So, Harry,\rdblquote  said Lockhart, while Hermione folded the note with fumbling fingers and slipped it into her bag. \ldblquote Tomorrow\rquote s the first Quidditch match of the season, I believe? Gryffindor against Slytherin, is it not? I hear you\rquote re a useful player. I was a Seeker, too. I was asked to try for the National Squad, but preferred to dedicate my life to the eradication of the Dark Forces. Still, if ever you feel the need for a little private training, don\rquote t hesitate to ask. Always happy to pass on my expertise to less able players. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry made an indistinct noise in his throat and then hurried off after Ron and Hermione.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t believe it,\rdblquote  he said as the three of them examined the signature on the note. \ldblquote He didn\rquote t even \i look\i0  at the book we wanted.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s because he\rquote s a brainless \i git,\i0\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote But who cares, we\rquote ve got what we needed \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He is \i not\i0  a brainless git,\rdblquote  said Hermione shrilly as they half ran toward the library.\par
\ldblquote Just because he said you were the best student of the year \emdash\rdblquote\par
They dropped their voices as they entered the muffled stillness of the library. Madam Pince, the librarian, was a thin, irritable woman who looked like an underfed vulture.\par
\ldblquote\i Moste Potente Potions\i0 ?\rdblquote  she repeated suspiciously, trying to take the note from Hermione; but Hermione wouldn\rquote t let go.\par
\ldblquote I was wondering if I could keep it,\rdblquote  she said breathlessly.\par
\ldblquote Oh, come on,\rdblquote  said Ron, wrenching it from her grasp and thrusting it at Madam Pince. \ldblquote We\rquote ll get you another autograph. Lockhart\rquote ll sign anything if it stands still long enough.\rdblquote\par
Madam Pince held the note up to the light, as though deter\-mined to detect a forgery, but it passed the test. She stalked away between the lofty shelves and returned several minutes later carry\-ing a large and moldy-looking book. Hermione put it carefully into her bag and they left, trying not to walk too quickly or look too guilty.\par
Five minutes later, they were barricaded in Moaning Myrtle\rquote s out-of-order bathroom once again. Hermione had overridden Ron\rquote s objections by pointing out that it was the last place anyone in their right minds would go, so they were guaranteed some privacy. Moaning Myrtle was crying noisily in her stall, but they were ig\-noring her, and she them.\par
Hermione opened \i Moste Potente Potions\i0  carefully, and the three of them bent over the damp-spotted pages. It was clear from a glance why it belonged in the Restricted Section. Some of the po\-tions had effects almost too gruesome to think about, and there were some very unpleasant illustrations, which included a man who seemed to have been turned inside out and a witch sprouting several extra pairs of arms out of her head.\par
\ldblquote Here it is,\rdblquote  said Hermione excitedly as she found the page headed \i The Polyjuice Potion.\i0  It was decorated with drawings of people halfway through transforming into other people. Harry sincerely hoped the artist had imagined the looks of intense pain on their faces.\par
\ldblquote This is the most complicated potion I\rquote ve ever seen,\rdblquote  said Hermione as they scanned the recipe. \ldblquote Lacewing flies, leeches, fluxweed, and knotgrass,\rdblquote  she murmured, running her finger down the list of ingredients. \ldblquote Well, they\rquote re easy enough, they\rquote re in the student store-cupboard, we can help ourselves. \'85 Oooh, look, powdered horn of a bicorn \emdash  don\rquote t know where we\rquote re going to get that \emdash  shredded skin of a boomslang \emdash  that\rquote ll be tricky, too \emdash  and of course a bit of whoever we want to change into.\rdblquote\par
