\lang1033 Harry woke early on Saturday morning and lay for a while think\-ing about the coming Quidditch match. He was nervous, mainly at the thought of what Wood would say if Gryffindor lost, but also at the idea of facing a team mounted on the fastest racing brooms gold could buy. He had never wanted to beat Slytherin so badly. After half an hour of lying there with his insides churning, he got up, dressed, and went down to breakfast early, where he found the rest of the Gryffindor team huddled at the long, empty table, all looking uptight and not speaking much.\par
\lang3081 As eleven o\rquote clock approached, the whole school started to make its way down to the Quidditch stadium. It was a muggy sort of day with a hint of thunder in the air. Ron and Hermione came hurry\-ing over to wish Harry good luck as he entered the locker rooms. The team pulled on their scarlet Gryffindor robes, then sat down to listen to Wood\rquote s usual pre-match pep talk.\par
\ldblquote Slytherin has better brooms than us,\rdblquote  he began. \ldblquote No point de\-nying it. But we\rquote ve got better \i people\i0  on our brooms. We\rquote ve trained harder than they have, we\rquote ve been flying in all weathers \emdash\rdblquote  (\ldblquote Too true,\rdblquote  muttered George Weasley. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t been properly dry since August\rdblquote ) \ldblquote\emdash  and we\rquote re going to make them rue the day they let that little bit of slime, Malfoy, buy his way onto their team.\rdblquote\par
Chest heaving with emotion, Wood turned to Harry.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote ll be down to you, Harry, to show them that a Seeker has to have something more than a rich father. Get to that Snitch before Malfoy or die trying, Harry, because we\rquote ve got to win today, we\rquote ve got to.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So no pressure, Harry,\rdblquote  said Fred, winking at him.\par
As they walked out onto the field, a roar of noise greeted them; mainly cheers, because Ravenclaw and Hufflepuff were anxious to see Slytherin beaten, but the Slytherins in the crowd made their boos and hisses heard, too. Madam Hooch, the Quidditch teacher, asked Flint and Wood to shake hands, which they did, giving each other threatening stares and gripping rather harder than was neces\-sary.\par
\ldblquote On my whistle,\rdblquote  said Madam Hooch. \ldblquote Three \'85 two \'85 one \'85\rdblquote\par
With a roar from the crowd to speed them upward, the fourteen players rose toward the leaden sky. Harry flew higher than any of them, squinting around for the Snitch.\par
\ldblquote All right there, Scarhead?\rdblquote  yelled Malfoy, shooting underneath him as though to show off the speed of his broom.\par
Harry had no time to reply. At that very moment, a heavy black Bludger came pelting toward him; he avoided it so narrowly that he felt it ruffle his hair as it passed.\par
\ldblquote Close one, Harry!\rdblquote  said George, streaking past him with his club in his hand, ready to knock the Bludger back toward a Slyth\-erin. Harry saw George give the Bludger a powerful whack in the direction of Adrian Pucey, but the Bludger changed direction in midair and shot straight for Harry again.\par
Harry dropped quickly to avoid it, and George managed to hit it hard toward Malfoy. Once again, the Bludger swerved like a boomerang and shot at Harry\rquote s head.\par
Harry put on a burst of speed and zoomed toward the other end of the field. He could hear the Bludger whistling along behind him. What was going on? Bludgers never concentrated on one player like this; it was their job to try and unseat as many people as possible. \'85\par
Fred Weasley was waiting for the Bludger at the other end. Harry ducked as Fred swung at the Bludger with all his might; the Bludger was knocked off course.\par
\ldblquote Gotcha!\rdblquote  Fred yelled happily, but he was wrong; as though it was magnetically attracted to Harry, the Bludger pelted after him once more and Harry was forced to fly off at full speed.\par
It had started to rain; Harry felt heavy drops fall onto his face, splattering onto his glasses. He didn\rquote t have a clue what was going on in the rest of the game until he heard Lee Jordan, who was com\-mentating, say, \ldblquote Slytherin lead, sixty points to zero \emdash\rdblquote\par
The Slytherins\rquote  superior brooms were clearly doing their jobs, and meanwhile the mad Bludger was doing all it could to knock Harry out of the air. Fred and George were now flying so close to him on either side that Harry could see nothing at all except their flailing arms and had no chance to look for the Snitch, let alone catch it.\par
\ldblquote Someone\rquote s \emdash  tampered \emdash  with \emdash  this \emdash  Bludger \emdash\rdblquote  Fred grunted, swinging his bat with all his might at it as it launched a new attack on Harry.\par
\ldblquote We need time out,\rdblquote  said George, trying to signal to Wood and stop the Bludger breaking Harry\rquote s nose at the same time.\par
Wood had obviously got the message. Madam Hooch\rquote s whistle rang out and Harry, Fred, and George dived for the ground, still trying to avoid the mad Bludger.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  said Wood as the Gryffindor team huddled together, while Slytherins in the crowd jeered. \ldblquote We\rquote re being flat\-tened. Fred, George, where were you when that Bludger stopped Angelina scoring?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We were twenty feet above her, stopping the other Bludger from murdering Harry, Oliver,\rdblquote  said George angrily. \ldblquote Someone\rquote s fixed it \emdash  it won\rquote t leave Harry alone. It hasn\rquote t gone for anyone else all game. The Slytherins must have done something to it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But the Bludgers have been locked in Madam Hooch\rquote s office since our last practice, and there was nothing wrong with them then. \'85\rdblquote  said Wood, anxiously.\par
Madam Hooch was walking toward them. Over her shoulder, Harry could see the Slytherin team jeering and pointing in his di\-rection.\par
\ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  said Harry as she came nearer and nearer, \ldblquote with you two flying around me all the time the only way I\rquote m going to catch the Snitch is if it flies up my sleeve. Go back to the rest of the team and let me deal with the rogue one.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be thick,\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote It\rquote ll take your head off.\rdblquote\par
Wood was looking from Harry to the Weasleys.\par
\ldblquote Oliver, this is insane,\rdblquote  said Alicia Spinnet angrily. \ldblquote You can\rquote t let Harry deal with that thing on his own. Let\rquote s ask for an inquiry \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If we stop now, we\rquote ll have to forfeit the match!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote And we\rquote re not losing to Slytherin just because of a crazy Bludger! Come on, Oliver, tell them to leave me alone!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote This is all your fault,\rdblquote  George said angrily to Wood. \ldblquote  \lquote Get the Snitch or die trying,\rquote  what a stupid thing to tell him \emdash\rdblquote\par
Madam Hooch had joined them.\par
\ldblquote Ready to resume play?\rdblquote  she asked Wood.\par
Wood looked at the determined look on Harry\rquote s face.\par
\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Fred, George, you heard Harry \emdash  leave him alone and let him deal with the Bludger on his own.\rdblquote\par
The rain was falling more heavily now. On Madam Hooch\rquote s whistle, Harry kicked hard into the air and heard the telltale whoosh of the Bludger behind him. Higher and higher Harry climbed; he looped and swooped, spiraled, zigzagged, and rolled. Slightly dizzy, he nevertheless kept his eyes wide open, rain was speckling his glasses and ran up his nostrils as he hung upside down, avoiding another fierce dive from the Bludger. He could hear laughter from the crowd; he knew he must look very stupid, but the rogue Bludger was heavy and couldn\rquote t change direction as quickly as Harry could; he began a kind of roller-coaster ride around the edges of the stadium, squinting through the silver sheets of rain to the Gryffindor goal posts, where Adrian Pucey was trying to get past Wood \emdash\par
A whistling in Harry\rquote s ear told him the Bludger had just missed him again; he turned right over and sped in the opposite direction.\par
\ldblquote Training for the ballet, Potter?\rdblquote  yelled Malfoy as Harry was forced to do a stupid kind of twirl in midair to dodge the Bludger, and he fled, the Bludger trailing a few feet behind him; and then, glaring back at Malfoy in hatred, he saw it \emdash  \i the Golden Snitch.\i0  It was hovering inches above Malfoy\rquote s left ear \emdash  and Malfoy, busy laughing at Harry, hadn\rquote t seen it.\par
For an agonizing moment, Harry hung in midair, not daring to speed toward Malfoy in case he looked up and saw the Snitch.\par
WHAM.\par
He had stayed still a second too long. The Bludger had hit him at last, smashed into his elbow, and Harry felt his arm break. Dimly, dazed by the searing pain in his arm, he slid sideways on his rain-drenched broom, one knee still crooked over it, his right arm dangling useless at his side \emdash  the Bludger came pelting back for a second attack, this time aiming at his face \emdash  Harry swerved out of the way, one idea firmly lodged in his numb brain: \i get to Malfoy.\i0\par
Through a haze of rain and pain he dived for the shimmering, sneering face below him and saw its eyes widen with fear: Malfoy thought Harry was attacking him.\par
\ldblquote What the \emdash\rdblquote  he gasped, careening out of Harry\rquote s way.\par
Harry took his remaining hand off his broom and made a wild snatch; he felt his fingers close on the cold Snitch but was now only gripping the broom with his legs, and there was a yell from the crowd below as he headed straight for the ground, trying hard not to pass out.\par
With a splattering thud he hit the mud and rolled off his broom. His arm was hanging at a very strange angle; riddled with pain, he heard, as though from a distance, a good deal of whistling and shouting. He focused on the Snitch clutched in his good hand.\par
\ldblquote Aha,\rdblquote  he said vaguely. \ldblquote We\rquote ve won.\rdblquote\par
And he fainted.\par
He came around, rain falling on his face, still lying on the field, with someone leaning over him. He saw a glitter of teeth.\par
\ldblquote Oh, no, not you,\rdblquote  he moaned.\par
\ldblquote Doesn\rquote t know what he\rquote s saying,\rdblquote  said Lockhart loudly to the anxious crowd of Gryffindors pressing around them. \ldblquote Not to worry, Harry. I\rquote m about to fix your arm.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i No\i0 !\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I\rquote ll keep it like this, thanks. \'85\rdblquote\par
He tried to sit up, but the pain was terrible. He heard a familiar clicking noise nearby.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t want a photo of this, Colin,\rdblquote  he said loudly.\par
\ldblquote Lie back, Harry,\rdblquote  said Lockhart soothingly. \ldblquote It\rquote s a simple charm I\rquote ve used countless times \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why can\rquote t I just go to the hospital wing?\rdblquote  said Harry through clenched teeth.\par
\ldblquote He should really, Professor,\rdblquote  said a muddy Wood, who couldn\rquote t help grinning even though his Seeker was injured. \ldblquote Great capture, Harry, really spectacular, your best yet, I\rquote d say \emdash\rdblquote\par
Through the thicket of legs around him, Harry spotted Fred and George Weasley, wrestling the rogue Bludger into a box. It was still putting up a terrific fight.\par
\ldblquote Stand back,\rdblquote  said Lockhart, who was rolling up his jade-green sleeves.\par
\ldblquote No \emdash  don\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry weakly, but Lockhart was twirling his wand and a second later had directed it straight at Harry\rquote s arm.\par
A strange and unpleasant sensation started at Harry\rquote s shoulder and spread all the way down to his fingertips. It felt as though his arm was being deflated. He didn\rquote t dare look at what was happen\-ing. He had shut his eyes, his face turned away from his arm, but his worst fears were realized as the people above him gasped and Colin Creevey began clicking away madly. His arm didn\rquote t hurt any\-more \emdash  nor did it feel remotely like an arm.\par
\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Lockhart. \ldblquote Yes. Well, that can sometimes happen. But the point is, the bones are no longer broken. That\rquote s the thing to bear in mind. So, Harry, just toddle up to the hospital wing \emdash  ah, Mr. Weasley, Miss Granger, would you escort him? \emdash  and Madam Pomfrey will be able to \emdash  er \emdash  tidy you up a bit.\rdblquote\par
As Harry got to his feet, he felt strangely lopsided. Taking a deep breath he looked down at his right side. What he saw nearly made him pass out again.\par
Poking out of the end of his robes was what looked like a thick, flesh-colored rubber glove. He tried to move his fingers. Nothing happened.\par
Lockhart hadn\rquote t mended Harry\rquote s bones. He had removed them.\par
\par
\lang1033 Madam Pomfrey wasn\rquote t at all pleased.\par
\lang3081\ldblquote You should have come straight to me!\rdblquote  she raged, holding up the sad, limp remainder of what, half an hour before, had been a working arm. \ldblquote I can mend bones in a second \emdash  but growing them back \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You will be able to, won\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Harry desperately.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be able to, certainly, but it will be painful,\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey grimly, throwing Harry a pair of pajamas. \ldblquote You\rquote ll have to stay the night. \'85\rdblquote\par
Hermione waited outside the curtain drawn around Harry\rquote s bed while Ron helped him into his pajamas. It took a while to stuff the rubbery, boneless arm into a sleeve.\par
\ldblquote How can you stick up for Lockhart now, Hermione, eh?\rdblquote  Ron called through the curtain as he pulled Harry\rquote s limp fingers through the cuff. \ldblquote If Harry had wanted deboning he would have asked.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Anyone can make a mistake,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote And it doesn\rquote t hurt anymore, does it, Harry?\rdblquote\par
